<br>
How about with Q66stang's &quot;quote&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>A velocity of 6 times Earth's escape velocity (67 km/sec, since escape velocity is 11.2 km/sec) would give the plate a kinetic energy 60% larger than the total energy released by the explosion. This is clearly impossible.<br>
<br>
Dr. Brownlee points that they were aware at the time that was not credible that the plate might actually might escape from Earth. Leaving aside whether such an extremely hypersonic unaerodynamic object could even survive passage through the lower atmosphere, it is impossible for it to retain much of its initial velocity while passing through the atmosphere A ground launched hypersonic projectile has the same problem with maintaining its velocity that an incoming meteor has.<br>
<br>
Of course the fact that the projectile was not found is no proof of a successful space launch. The cylinder and cover plate of Pascal-A were also not found, even though no hypersonic projectile was involved. Even speeds typical of ordinary artillery can send an object many kilometers, beyond the area of any reasonable search effort.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Okay.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, let's look at the original, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>unedited</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> quote..<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>If the description of the plate is accurate - 4 feet wide, 4 inches thick and made of steel - then it would weigh about 900 kg (a lower weight is possible if the dimensions are inaccurate or if it was not of uniform thickness).</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> A velocity of 6 times Earth's escape velocity (67 km/sec, since escape velocity is 11.2 km/sec) would give the plate a kinetic energy 60% larger than the total energy released by the explosion. This is clearly impossible.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Brownlee explained to this author, by email, that the concrete plug placed in close proximity to the bomb was vaporized by the explosion. Thus the propulsion of the plate could be considered to be due to the energy imparted by this expanding vaporized material, rather like the propellant of a gun. From the descriptions available of the plug a mass of at least 3000 kg can be estimated, and if half the bomb's energy were deposited in it then it would have an energy density of 50 times that of normal gun propellant. From the physics of high velocity guns, it can be estimated that velocities produced by the gas expanding up the long shaft could propel and object to velocities exceeding Earth's escape velocity, perhaps as much as twice escape velocity.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Dr. Brownlee points that they were aware at the time that was not credible that the plate might actually might escape from Earth. Leaving aside whether such an extremely hypersonic unaerodynamic object could even survive passage through the lower atmosphere, it is impossible for it to retain much of its initial velocity while passing through the atmosphere. A ground launched hypersonic projectile has the same problem with maintaining its velocity that an incoming meteor has. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>According to the American Meteor Society Fireball and Meteor FAQ meteors weighing less than 8 tonnes retain none of their cosmic velocity when passing through the atmosphere, they simply end up as a falling rock. Only objects weighing many times this mass retain a significant fraction of their velocity.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Of course the fact that the projectile was not found is no proof of a successful space launch. The cylinder and cover plate of Pascal-A were also not found, even though no hypersonic projectile was involved. Even speeds typical of ordinary artillery can send an object many kilometers, beyond the area of any reasonable search effort.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
(emphasis mine, on parts missing from actual quote)<br>
<br>
Now, first let's notice that Q66stang removed fully half of the actual, original quote before putting it up as an argument in his favor.<br>
<br>
I believe this is referred to as &quot;evidence tampering&quot;.<br>
<br>
Let's look at just what was edited out:<br>
<br>
The first bold section estimates the plate to be at an approximate mass of 900kg or less.  Iff we look to the last bold section, we can intuit why those two parts were cut from Q66stang's &quot;quoting&quot; of the article.<br>
<br>
If only objects weighing greater than 8 tonnes (certainly more than 900kg) will retain significant atmospheric velocity, then a 300 - 8,000,000 tonne Orion should have no problems whatsoever, ne..?<br>
<br>
Now..from the portion of the first paragraph that he left intact..he takes issue with the 6x-escape velocity issue.<br>
<br>
To that, firstly, I would like to suggest that no-one is going to design and develop any craft that significantly exceeds minimum escape velocity.  It's not possible, practical, economic or necessary.  An Orion would be designed to overcome simple EV and no more..there's no need, at all.<br>
<br>
Secondly, I would suggest that..for all he accuses myself of not reading (I guess &quot;reading&quot; and &quot;Selective-editing&quot; are similar in his personal lexicon) the article, he seems to have missed the entire article from which this one was linked..<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
When I described my results to Bill Ogle, the conversation went something like this. <br>
<br>
Ogle: &quot;What time does the shock arrive at the top of the pipe?&quot;<br>
RRB: &quot;Thirty one milliseconds.&quot;<br>
Ogle: &quot;And what happens?&quot;<br>
RRB: &quot;The shock reflects back down the hole, but the pressures and temperatures are such that the welded cap is bound to come off the hole.&quot;<br>
Ogle: &quot;How fast does it go?&quot;<br>
RRB: &quot;My calculations are irrelevant on this point. They are only valid in speaking of the shock reflection.&quot;<br>
Ogle: &quot;How fast did it go?&quot;<br>
RRB: &quot;Those numbers are meaningless. I have only a vacuum above the cap. No air, no gravity, no real material strengths in the iron cap. Effectively the cap is just loose, traveling through meaningless space.&quot;<br>
Ogle: And how fast is it going?&quot;<br>
<br>
This last question was more of a shout. Bill liked to have a direct answer to each one of his questions.<br>
<br>
RRB: &quot;Six times the escape velocity from the earth.&quot;   <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Here, &quot;speed&quot; is being referenced by comparison to EV..in the same way that astronomical distances are referenced by AUs.  There was no intent to related the figure to the reality of an actual ground launch.<br>
<br>
In essence, a space-launch Orion would achieve such speeds from the yield used in the test..simulation testing.<br>
<br>
This is important when we consider the second, entire paragraph, that Q66stang has edited out of his &quot;quote&quot;.<br>
<br>
Based upon the information gleaned from this particular test..according to the author that Q66stang &quot;quotes&quot;..1 to 2 times escape velocity would be physically, actually attained.<br>
<br>
Therefore, the accidental launching..whether or not it ever escaped earth's gravity or did not burn up in the atmosphere (it was never designed for, nor intended for, launch testing..) is valid experimental evidence.<br>
<br>
To continue, he manages to leave in the part of the article that says &quot;it is impossible for it to retain much of it's initial velocity while passing through the atmosphere..&quot;<br>
<br>
Forgive me if I'm wrong, but isn't the whole point of the Orion that it's a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>pulsed</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> drive system..?  Initial blast, followed by detonation upon detonation..every second or three..to maintain and increase launch velocity..?  Not even remotely wholly reliant upon a single detonation on the ground..?<br>
<br>
Thought so.<br>
<br>
There <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>isn't</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> any &quot;initial velocity&quot; that needs to be &quot;maintained&quot;, for there would be the constant application of new thrust.<br>
<br>
What next..?  Oh, yes...<br>
<br>
The last portion of the &quot;quote&quot; that Q66stang actually left intact suggests that &quot;ordinary artillery&quot; can &quot;send an object...beyond the area of any reasonable search..&quot;<br>
<br>
Of course, this &quot;ordinary artillery&quot; has not been calculated..based upon real numbers from a real test..to lob a projectile at  &quot;perhaps as much as twice escape velocity&quot;.<br>
<br>
There's a fundamental difference, there.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
I disagree my short-peckered friend – its clear you didn’t read the entire article before shooting off your mouth and making a complete fool of yourself.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
To the latter part of that;  I think I've made it reasonably clear as to who read all the documentation..and, as well, who didn't edit material to suit one's personal agenda.<br>
<br>
As to the former;  stop thinking about my body.  It creeps me out and I'm not interested...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Now do you understand why your opinion means nothing?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Because you have difficulty comprehending simple concepts..?<br>
<br>
